Re: What does 〜て　おきます mean?
by milly » Mon 09.06.2010 8:26 pm Thank you very much for your response. So what you're saying is that:"〜て　おきます" actually means "I shall have (verb - past participle) 〜" ?e.g.: 宿題を　して　おきます。(I shall have done/finished the homework.)BUT "しまいます" also means "will have done" so what is the difference between these two?e.g.: 宿題を　して　しまいます。(I will have done/finished the homework.)--------------------------------------------------------Previously, I mentioned "意向形動詞" in my last post. I'm afraid I didn't make myself clear enough. Please have a look at the following examples.e.g.1: 買います-->買おうe.g.2: 覚えます-->覚えよう(Verbs in the second column are called 意向形動詞)I thought "〜て　おきます" means "I am going to 〜" and sentences with 意向形動詞 would also have similar meanings so I just raised a question about the difference between "〜て　おきます" and "sentences with 意向形動詞". e.g.: 買い物に　行こう。(I shall/am going to go shopping.)Am I right?I guess I got mixed up with different types of grammar in Japanese. I'm afraid my post may be a bit long so thank you for your patience.
milly
